WHEREAS George Walker Bush, President of the United State, engaged in an inappropriate relationship with a foreign nation in the White House, which was shameful, reckless and indefensible;

 WHEREAS George Walker Bush, President of the United State, deliberately misled and deceived the American people, and people in all branches of the United States government;

 WHEREAS George Walker Bush, President of the United State, gave false or misleading testimony and his actions have had the effect of impeding discovery of evidence in judicial proceedings;

 WHEREAS George Walker Bush's conduct in this matter is unacceptable for a President of the United States, does demean the office of the President as well as the President himself, and creates disrespect for the laws of the land;

 WHEREAS President Bush fully deserves censure for engaging in such behavior;

 WHEREAS future generations of Americans must know that such behavior is not only unacceptable but also bears grave consequences, including loss of integrity, trust and respect;

 WHEREAS George Walker Bush remains subject to criminal actions in a court law like any other citizen; 

 WHEREAS George Walker Bush's conduct in this matter has brought shame and dishonor to himself and to the Office of the President; and 

 WHEREAS George Walker Bush though his conduct in this matter has violated the trust of the American people;

 NOW THEREFORE BE IT RESOLVED THAT:

 The United States Senate does hereby censure George Walker Bush, President of the United States, and does condemn his wrongful conduct in the strongest terms; and

 NOW BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED THAT:

 The United States Senate recognizes the historic gravity of this resolution, and trusts and urges that future congresses will recognize the importance of allowing this statement of censure and condemnation to remain intact for all time; and

 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED THAT: 

 The Senate now move on to other matters of significance, such as serious consideration of the situation in Iraq, the matter of accountability in all matters pertaining to Iraq, fiscal responsibility and stopping the deep slide into deficit, and other matters that the Senate and the other Legislative branch have neglected because of the actions of the President.
